import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv(r"D:\Desktop\Excel\Amazon_datasets.csv")

# -----------------------------
# 1 Price vs Rating Scatter Plot
# -----------------------------
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.scatterplot(data=df, x='price', y='rating', hue='category', alpha=0.7)
plt.title("Price vs Rating by Category")
plt.xlabel("Price")
plt.ylabel("Rating")
plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# -----------------------------
# 2 Premium Categories (High Price + High Rating)
# -----------------------------
category_stats = df.groupby('category').agg({
    'price':'mean',
    'rating':'mean'
}).sort_values(by=['price','rating'], ascending=False)

print("Premium Categories (High Price + High Rating):\n")
print(category_stats.head(10))  # Top 10 premium categories

# -----------------------------
# 3 Budget-Friendly Categories (Low Price + Good Rating)
# -----------------------------
budget_friendly = category_stats[(category_stats['price'] < category_stats['price'].median()) & 
                                 (category_stats['rating'] >= 4.0)]

print("\nBudget-Friendly Categories (Low Price + Good Rating):\n")
print(budget_friendly.sort_values(by='rating', ascending=False))

# Requirements: pandas, numpy, seaborn, matplotlib
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load dataset: replace filename as needed
df = pd.read_csv(r"D:\Desktop\Excel\Amazon_datasets.csv")

# Ensure numeric types
df['price'] = pd.to_numeric(df['price'], errors='coerce')
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')

# Drop rows missing key fields (or handle per your policy)
df = df.dropna(subset=['category', 'price', 'rating'])

# 1) Distribution of products across different categories
cat_counts = df['category'].value_counts().rename_axis('category').reset_index(name='count')
cat_counts['percent'] = 100 * cat_counts['count'] / cat_counts['count'].sum()

print("Category distribution (count & %):")
print(cat_counts)

# Bar plot: counts by category
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.barplot(data=cat_counts, x='count', y='category', palette='viridis')
plt.title('Number of products per category')
plt.xlabel('Count')
plt.ylabel('Category')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig('category_counts.png')
plt.close()

import pandas as pd
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv(r"D:\Desktop\Excel\Amazon_datasets.csv")

# Convert to numeric where needed
df['price'] = pd.to_numeric(df['price'], errors='coerce')
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')

# Drop rows with missing values
df = df.dropna(subset=['category','price','rating'])

# Category counts
cat_counts = df['category'].value_counts()

# Bar chart using pyplot
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.barh(cat_counts.index, cat_counts.values, color="skyblue")
plt.xlabel("Number of Products")
plt.ylabel("Category")
plt.title("Number of Products per Category (Amazon Dataset)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv(r"D:\Desktop\Excel\Amazon_datasets.csv")

# Clean
df['price'] = pd.to_numeric(df['price'], errors='coerce')
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')
df = df.dropna(subset=['category','price','rating'])

# Category counts
cat_counts = df['category'].value_counts()

# Pie chart
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
plt.pie(
    cat_counts.values,
    labels=cat_counts.index,
    autopct='%1.1f%%',       # show percentage
    startangle=90,           # rotate so first slice starts at top
    counterclock=False
)
plt.title("Distribution of Products per Category")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv(r"D:\Desktop\Excel\Amazon_datasets.csv")

# Clean
df['price'] = pd.to_numeric(df['price'], errors='coerce')
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')
df = df.dropna(subset=['category','price','rating'])

# Correlation matrix (only numeric cols)
corr = df[['price','rating']].corr()

# Heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, cmap="coolwarm", fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)
plt.title("Correlation Heatmap (Price vs Rating)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Violin Plot of Prices per Category
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load dataset
df = pd.read_csv(r"D:\Desktop\Excel\Amazon_datasets.csv")

# Clean
df['price'] = pd.to_numeric(df['price'], errors='coerce')
df['rating'] = pd.to_numeric(df['rating'], errors='coerce')
df = df.dropna(subset=['category','price','rating'])

# Violin plot: Price distribution across categories
plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))
sns.violinplot(data=df, x="category", y="price", palette="Set2")
plt.title("Price Distribution by Category (Violin Plot)")
plt.xlabel("Category")
plt.ylabel("Price")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
